Based on my review of the TechSpec, ADRs, research analyses, lessons learned, and the existing codebase (extension protocol, MCP auth, SDK structure), here is my verdict.

```json
{
  "blockers": [
    {
      "id": "B-001",
      "section": "Implementation Design / Core Interfaces + Integration Points / Extensions",
      "issue": "The ExtensionToolInvoker interface is pasted, but the structs it depends on — ExtensionToolCallRequest and the matching response/runtime payload that the TS SDK, Go SDK, and daemon must all serialize identically — are referenced as named types and never defined as Go code blocks. The wire shape of the new extension service methods 'tool.provider' / 'provide_tools' / 'tools/call' is also not registered the way existing host_api.go ExtensionServiceMethod constants are (memory/store, memory/recall, bridges/deliver). Three independent implementations (sdk/typescript, sdk/go, internal/extension/protocol + internal/extension/manager) plus the registry adapter are required to converge on a wire that the spec does not draw.",
      "rationale": "L-012 (`techspec-prose-only-rework`) is explicit that contract-laden surfaces require concrete Go interface signatures pasted as code blocks; otherwise reviewers converge N implementations across N rework rounds. ADR-001 and ADR-008 both depend on bit-identical wire descriptors for manifest/runtime reconciliation, and the existing protocol package treats every AGH→extension method as a typed constant. Leaving the new methods undefined will repeat the autonomy-vs-release-adjustments review trajectory described in L-012.",
      "suggested_fix": "Paste, in the TechSpec, full Go struct definitions for ExtensionToolCallRequest, ExtensionToolCallResponse, ExtensionProvideToolsResponse (or equivalent), MCPToolCallRequest, and MCPToolCallResponse, plus the `internal/extension/protocol` additions: `CapabilityProvideToolProvider = \"tool.provider\"`, `ExtensionServiceMethodProvideTools = \"provide_tools\"`, `ExtensionServiceMethodToolsCall = \"tools/call\"`, and their entry in `capabilityServiceMethods`. State explicitly which fields are wire-stable (digests, ToolID, handler) vs runtime-only (latency, content blocks)."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-002",
      "section": "Data Models / ExtensionToolRuntimeDescriptor + ADR-008 Implementation Notes",
      "issue": "Manifest/runtime reconciliation requires `input_schema_digest` and `output_schema_digest` to match exactly between the manifest, the TS SDK helper output, the Go SDK helper output, and the daemon's manifest validator. The TechSpec never specifies the digest algorithm, byte canonicalization, or normalization rules (key ordering, escape behavior, integer/number representation, $ref handling). Without this, identical schemas will hash differently across language toolchains and produce false `extension_runtime_mismatch` reason codes — exactly the runtime-vs-test-fixture drift class L-007 calls out.",
      "rationale": "ADR-008 makes digests load-bearing for the executable boundary; CLAUDE.md's hard-cut rule means the only allowed correction post-MVP is rip-and-replace, not adding a 'lenient' fallback. A digest spec that depends on whichever JSON serializer each SDK happens to use is not a contract. Greenfield posture forbids 'try strict, then loose' fallbacks.",
      "suggested_fix": "In the TechSpec, mandate digest = `sha256(JCS-canonicalized JSON Schema)` per RFC 8785 (or an equivalent fully-specified canonicalization), hex-encoded lowercase. Specify which subtree is hashed (the schema only, not surrounding manifest metadata). Require a shared conformance fixture under `sdk/typescript/test-fixtures/digest/` and `sdk/go/.../digest/` consumed by both SDK tests and `internal/extension/manifest_test.go` so all three implementations regress against the same byte vectors."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-003",
      "section": "Implementation Design / Core Interfaces + ADR-010 Implementation Notes",
      "issue": "The spec correctly forbids `internal/tools` from holding remote-MCP token material and exposes only the redacted `MCPAuthStatusProvider.Status`. But remote-MCP `tools/call` over HTTP/SSE requires injecting a live `Authorization: Bearer …` header per call. No interface signature is pasted that lets the registry trigger a remote call without the registry ever touching the token: ADR-010 only mentions `narrow internal/mcp/auth execution interfaces for bearer material` in prose. MCPTolInvoker.CallTool takes only `(ctx, source, req)` and returns ToolResult; where the bearer is acquired and bound to the request is unspecified.",
      "rationale": "Security invariant 20 makes `internal/mcp/auth` the sole credential owner; invariant 12 forbids any raw token in tool inputs/outputs. Without a code-block contract for the call-through executor, implementers will end up either (a) plumbing a TokenStore reference into the registry adapter (token ownership leak) or (b) creating a parallel auth helper that re-fetches tokens and drifts from `internal/mcp/auth.Service`. Both outcomes violate L-005 (authoritative primitive exclusivity) and the ADR-010 'do not duplicate MCP auth' rule.",
      "suggested_fix": "Paste an `MCPCallExecutor` interface owned by `internal/mcp` (consuming `internal/mcp/auth` directly), e.g. `type MCPCallExecutor interface { Call(ctx context.Context, source SourceRef, req MCPToolCallRequest) (ToolResult, error) }`, document that it internally resolves token material from `mcpauth.TokenStore` without exposing TokenRecord, and prohibit `internal/tools` from importing `internal/mcp/auth` at all. Add a redaction test that mounts a fake remote MCP and asserts that no `Authorization` header value crosses any error/log/event boundary owned by `internal/tools`."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-004",
      "section": "Hosted MCP authentication",
      "issue": "The hosted_mcp_bind_token is required to be redacted 'like claim_token' but the spec passes the raw token through ACP `mcpServers[].env`, which is part of the `session/new` / `session/load` payload sent to an external agent runtime that AGH does not control. CLAUDE.md says 'claim_token (raw) never crosses transport, channel, log, or memory.' Treating the bind token as claim_token-equivalent and then handing it to a third-party process via the ACP wire is internally contradictory. Redaction tests cover 'ACP payload diagnostics' as observed by AGH, but cannot cover the spawned ACP runtime's own logging/env-dump behavior.",
      "rationale": "Standing directive on truthful UI / claim_token redaction, plus L-005 (one authority per primitive), forbids design choices where a security-equivalent secret silently leaves the daemon's redaction perimeter. Either the bind token is genuinely claim_token-equivalent (then it must not cross the ACP wire) or it is a different class of secret with its own threat model — but the spec must choose one.",
      "suggested_fix": "Either (a) replace env-injection with a UDS challenge: spawn the proxy with only `--session <id>` and a short-lived `bind_nonce`, then complete a UDS handshake where the daemon mints the session-bound projection bound to the proxy's pid+uds-per-cred without ever shipping a reusable token through ACP env; or (b) document an explicit threat-model section stating 'bind_token traverses ACP env to external runtimes; mitigations are single-use, ≤Ns TL, session-bound, hash-only persistence' and rename the redaction equivalence: 'redacted in AGH-owned surfaces; cannot be redacted in third-party agent logs.' Pick one and update Security Invariant 16 to match exactly."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-005",
      "section": "Hosted MCP approval bridge",
      "issue": "The bridge says `Registry.Call` 'blocks the MCP `tools/call` response until approved, denied, or timed out' but no timeout, no config key, no default, and no cancellation semantics are defined. ACP `session/request_permission` is unbounded; an unresponsive operator or a half-closed ACP stream will hold a goroutine and an MCP RPC indefinitely. The spec also gives no behavior when the hosted MCP stdio closes mid-approval.",
      "rationale": "Detached lifetime + WaitGroup discipline (internal/CLAUDE.md Concurrency) plus 'External-call timeouts' security invariant require every blocking external dependency to have an explicit deadline. An approval that blocks an in-flight tool call is a long-running external dependency, and the spec leaves it unbounded.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add `[tools.policy].approval_timeout_seconds` (default e.g. 120) to the Config Lifecycle section; define reason codes `approval_timed_out` and `approval_canceled`; specify that `Registry.Call` uses a derived context with the approval deadline, and that closing the hosted MCP stdio cancels the in-flight approval and returns `ErrToolApprovalRequired` with `approval_canceled`. Add an integration test for both timeout and proxy-disconnect-mid-approval paths."
    }
